
When events occur (or is fired) a reference of event object is passed to any function that is the event handler or listener. 
To pass arguments to a named function,
FIRST: The EVENT OBJECT will be passed to the anonymous wrapper function. (automatically)
SECOND: Then EVENT OBJECT is specified as a parameter(e = event) of the named function.

The name (e) can be used in the function as a reference to the OBJECT EVENT. 
The reference allows the use of the properties and methods of the EVENT OBJECT. [EG. target, ]

EVENT LISTENER WITH NO PARAMETERS
              function checkName(e) {  // here function defined and parameter named e pass as reference from call of checkUsername at 1.
                  var target = e.target;           // get target of event 
                 // the reference to e allows the properties and methods of event object to be used here.
                 // EVENT OBJECT which can be used. [Properties: target, type, cancelable; Methods: preventDefault(), stopPropagation() ]
                };
                var el = document.getElementByid('username');
                el.addEventlistener('blur', 1.checkUsername, false);


EVENT LISTENER WITH PARAMETERS
              function checkUsername(e, minlength) {
                  var target = e .target ;         //get target of event
              }
              var el = document.getElementByid('username') ;
              el .addEventlistener('blur', function(e){
                      checkUsername(e, 5);
                } , false);
          
